Part I - (PISA 2012 Dataset Analysis)¶

by (Saeed Ashri)¶

Introduction¶

In this project, we will analyse the dataset of PISA 2012. This dataset is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. This survey is about how well-prepared they are for life beyond school. This dataset has 4885490 students. The stages of this project go through preliminary wrangling of data, univariate exploration, bivariate exploration, and multivariate exploration. Then, the key findings explain in the conclusion.

#Function for put contry states and diffrent name of contry in one value
def changeCountry(df):
    
    if df['Country_code'] in ['Connecticut (USA)', 'Florida (USA)', 'Massachusetts (USA)', 'United States of America']:
        return 'USA'
    elif df['Country_code'] in ['Russian Federation', 'Perm(Russian Federation)']:
        return'Russia'
    elif df['Country_code'] in ['United Kingdom']:
        return 'UK'
    elif df['Country_code'] in ['United Arab Emirates']:
        return 'UAE'
    elif df['Country_code'] in ['China-Shanghai', 'Macao-China', 'Macao']:
        return 'China'
    elif df['Country_code'] in ['Hong Kong-China']:
        return 'Hong Kong'
    elif df['Country_code'] in ['Czechia', 'Czech Republic']:
        return 'Czech'
    elif df['Country_code'] in ['Chinese Taipei']:
        return 'Taiwan'
    else:
        return df['Country_code']

pisa_df['Country'] = pisa_df.apply(lambda pisa_df : changeCountry(pisa_df), axis=1)

# Transform 6 columns to one column (with_Family)

def transformColumns(df):
    if df['have_Mother'] == 'Yes' or df['have_Father'] == 'Yes' or df['have_Brothers'] == 'Yes' or df['have_Sisters'] == 'Yes' or df['have_Grandparents'] == 'Yes' or df['have_Any_Part_family'] == 'Yes':
            return True
    else:
        return False
    
pisa_df['with_Family'] = pisa_df.apply(lambda pisa_df: transformColumns(pisa_df), axis=1)
        
pisa_df.drop(['have_Mother', 'have_Father', 'have_Brothers', 'have_Sisters', 'have_Grandparents', 'have_Any_Part_family'], axis=1, inplace=True)

#Function helps to replace symbles of level education 

def levelOfEducation(df):
    if df['Parents_Highest_Education'] in ['ISCED 1']:
        return 'Primary education'
    elif df['Parents_Highest_Education'] in ['ISCED 2']:
        return  'Lower secondary education'
    elif df['Parents_Highest_Education'] in ['ISCED 3A' , 'ISCED 3B, C']:
        return 'Upper secondary education'
    elif df['Parents_Highest_Education'] in ['ISCED 4']:
        return 'Post-secondary non-tertiary education'
    elif df['Parents_Highest_Education'] in ['ISCED 5B']:
        return 'Short-cycle tertiary or Bachelor’s'
    elif df['Parents_Highest_Education'] in ['ISCED 5A, 6']:
        return ' Master’s, or Doctoral'
    else:
        return 'Early childhood education'
In [35]:
# Apply function to dataset
pisa_df['Parents_Highest_Education'] = pisa_df.apply(lambda pisa_df : levelOfEducation(pisa_df), axis=1)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of scores in Math, Reading, and Science is normal distribution. However, the distribution of time study out-of-school is skewed right but we scale as logarithmic to be normal distribution.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

As can be seen, the features of the time of study out of school are skewed right. So, we decided to sum all time of study out of school to get the total study out-of-school time. Then, we used a logarithmic scale to total study out-of-school time to get normal distribution.

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, After wrangling the dataset, we start analysing the dataset in three sections. The first section is Univariate which see the distribution of math, reading and science scores. Also, the unusual distribution that we found is for each time study out of school which skewed to the right until we get the total time of study out of school and scale it as logarithmic to get normal distribution. The second section is Bivariate which explores two features together. So, we examine the relationship between scores in math, reading, and science together. So, we found all of them have positive relationships. Also, we examine the relationship between scores and gender. So, we found reading scores and females related to others. The third section is Multivariate which explore three feature in one plot. in this section we examine the relationship between Scores of subjects, parents' level of education, and gender so, we don't find any relation between them except with reading scores. Also, we explore the relationship between scores and parents' level of education, and language at home. So, we found high scores for students who speak the same test language and parents has master's or doctoral. Moreover, we explore scores of subjects, language at home, and mother and father his job. we found students who speak the language as a test and their mothers and fathers have full-time jobs has high scores.
